ror." Scrupulously researched and devoid of rhetoric, the book deepens the story of post-9/11 America and the nation’s descent into the netherworld of prisoner abuse. Researchers interviewed more than sixty former Guantánamo detainees in nine countries, as well as key government officials, military experts, former guards, interrogators, lawyers for detainees, and other camp personnel. We hear directly from former detainees as they describe the events surrounding their capture, their years of incarceration, and the myriad difficulties preventing many from resuming a normal life upon returning home. Prepared jointly by researchers with the Human Rights Center, University of California, Berkeley, and the International Human Rights Law Clinic, University of California, Berkeley School of Law, in partnership with the Center for Constitutional Rights, The Guantánamo Effect contributes significantly to the debate surrounding the U.S.’s commitment to international law during war time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDetention of personszCubazGuantánamo Bay Naval Base. 0aPrisoners of warzCubazGuantánamo Bay Naval Base. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPrisoners and prisons, American. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a21st century american military history.  aamerican military practices.  abush administration.  acapture.  acenter for constitutional rights.  acuba.  aformer prisoners.  aguantanamo bay.  aguantanamo.  ahuman rights center.  aincarceration.  ainternational human rights law clinic.  ainternational law.  ainterrogation.  anational security.  apolitical.  apost 9/11 america.  apresident george w bush.  aprisoner abuse.  aunited states of america.  aus detention.  aus interrogation practices.  awar on terror.  awar time laws.1 aFletc